article.headline: Douby outduels fellow freshman Stinson
article.story: AMES, Iowa (AP) -- Curtis Stinson says he wants to set an example for Iowa State's newcomers. They'd be well served to pay attention. Stinson, hoping to follow up on a sensational freshman season, showed his versatility in helping the Cyclones beat Division II Bemidji State 80-57 Tuesday night in their first exhibition game. The 6-foot-3 guard did a little of everything, scoring 14 points, grabbing nine rebounds, handing out eight assists and making five steals. "Last year, everybody showed me the moves. Now it's my turn to be an example," Stinson said. "I'm trying to get them to have confidence, distribute the ball and play my role. That's what we try to do, get all of these guys involved." Junior college transfer Anthony Davis was the most impressive of the newcomers with 13 points on 5-for-7 shooting. Freshman Rahshon Clark shot 4-for-5 in scoring nine points and JC transfer Robert Faulkner added six points, making all three of his shots. Will Blalock, also impressive as a freshman last season, matched Stinson with 14 points, 13 in the first half. Blalock went 6-for-9 from the field, including a 3-pointer, and handed out six assists. "I feel a lot stronger this year," Blalock said. "Last year I settled for a lot of jumpers and I looked to pass. With this team, I have to be a lot more offensive-minded." Jared Homan, Iowa State's only senior, had nine points, six rebounds and three blocks. John Neal hit two 3-pointers and scored eight points. Iowa State outscored Bemidji State 28-14 over the final 12:13 of the first half to open a 45-28 lead. Bemidji State drew to 46-39 early in the second half before the Cyclones put on another burst to pull away. "We went on a drought," Blalock said. "We didn't execute as well, made some mistakes and turned it over. They rebounded well. The offensive rebounds killed us." Iowa State gave up 15 offensive rebounds and committed 21 turnovers but shot 56 percent. Derrick Beechum led Bemidji State with 16 points.
